master: fix provider reference leak, cold-start kill, and one-shot power-cycling (v3)

Upstream-Status: Inappropriate [upstream abandoned, geoclue1 superseded by geoclue2]

v3 adds a 30-second linger before provider shutdown. Field testing (v2)
surfaced that one-shot consumers - e.g. asteroid-map requesting a single
position rather than streaming - subscribe and unsubscribe within
seconds. With shutdown working (v2), every such request power-cycled the
GPS, forcing a cold start each time and never acquiring a fix. Now
gc_master_provider_unsubscribe() schedules deinitialize on a 30s
g_timeout instead of calling it directly; any re-subscribe cancels the
pending shutdown. The timeout is also cancelled in dispose. 30s is a
tunable compromise: long enough to bridge repeated one-shot requests
and app restarts, short enough to bound the power cost after real use
ends.

v2: keep not-yet-available (ACQUIRING) candidate providers subscribed
during provider selection - unsubscribing them was only harmless while
provider shutdown was disabled; with shutdown re-enabled it killed a
cold-starting GPS within a second of starting it (the bug the original
author dodged in 2008 by disabling shutdown instead of fixing
selection).

v1: the master daemon had no working dereference path at all:
GcMasterClient Add/RemoveReference were TODO no-ops, master never
destroyed client objects nor watched app bus names, and the provider
shutdown call was commented out. Fix: real per-sender refcounting on
GcMasterClient mirroring gc-provider.c, NameOwnerChanged watch to clean
up after crashed apps, client self-destruction at zero references
(idle-deferred), and re-enabled provider shutdown.

Field record: v2 confirmed on medaka 2026-07-19 (cold start acquires,
shutdown on app close, in-session restart works). v3 linger path
compile-checked, not yet field-tested; the one-shot scenario needs an
asteroid-map-style consumer to verify.

Needs dbus-glib >= 0.90. Apply with patch -p1 (replaces v1/v2 entirely).

